node.text: Does your new houseplant need a new home? Transplanting them into larger pots will help them grow better, bigger, and stronger. But growth isn’t the only reason to repot: You may have a plant that looks a little sickly and in need of a nutrient boost, which it’ll get when you add new soil to its current container. Watch plant expert Katura Barnes (@terracottahotties) share her tips for repotting houseplants including what containers she loves to use and what combination of soil she prefers for her plant babies. https://bit.ly/3xUw5OC

node.text: Hydrangeas are deciduous shrubs that put on a beautiful color show during their blooming seasons. They come in many varieties: some bloom on old wood, while others prefer to flower only after a careful pruning on new wood. For the former, which include panicle hydrangea and smooth hydrangea, horticulturist Stacey Hirvela notes that you will need to start tending to your plants as early as March. And for the latter? Varieties like bigleaf hydrangea, mountain hydrangea, and oakleaf hydrangea require much less work throughout the year. In our month-by-month hydrangea care guide, we share what to do to your favorite flower shrub at the correct time - visit the link in bio to learn more!

node.text: Looking for inspiration for using up that basket of peaches? Use them in a mouthwatering dessert, like this delicious and easy fruit buckle. A cross between a cake-like cobbler and a traditional fruit crumble, a buckle is the perfect way to showcase those juicy summer peaches. Get the Martha Bakes recipe here or at the link in bio: https://bit.ly/3rqdibj

node.text: Does your new houseplant need a new home? Transplanting them into larger pots will help them grow better, bigger, and stronger. But growth isn’t the only reason to repot: You may have a plant that looks a little sickly and in need of a nutrient boost, which it’ll get when you add new soil to its current container. Watch plant expert Katura Barnes (@terracottahotties) share her tips for repotting houseplants including what containers she loves to use and what combination of soil she prefers for her plant babies. https://bit.ly/3xUw5OC

node.text: Splatter painting is a fun and easy way to jazz up plain table linens (T-shirts and sneakers, too). We used Kaufman Essex Linen-Blend Fabric in Cadet and Southern Classic Linen-Blend Fabric in white as our canvases of choice. All you need is a squeeze bottle, paint, and fabric medium (to thin the contents a bit). Shake it up, then drip, drip, drip, and dry. Get the full tutorial in our July/August issue or at the link in bio. 📷: @linda.xiao created + styled by: @naomidemanana

node.text: Whether cantaloupe, honeydew, or watermelon, sweet and juicy melon is the fruit of high summer. 🍈 When the temperatures soar and the humidity is intense, melon is refreshing blended into a delicious drink. Inspired by fruity Mexican aguas frescas, these thirst quenchers are like a dip in the pool on a steamy day. The formula for each of the three recipes is the same: stir up one of our herbal simple syrups, then see what it can do with a little chopped melon, fresh citrus juice, a splash of water, and a handful of ice. Get the recipes featured in our July/August issue at the link im bio. 📷: @linda.xiao recipe + food styling by: @flossylucille prop styling by: @suzie_myers
